Midgaard's trade ledger records payment received for condemned-subject transfers during the Spirebound Conclave period, classified as cargo and payment amounts rather than by race or origin.
Continuity faction: opening Kowloon's Black Ledger is reciprocally destructive — any proceeding examining Kowloon's delta settlements necessarily examines Midgaard's payment records.
Practical arrangement is mutual suppression: Midgaard and Kowloon Continuity factions share no formal agreement, but their interests align; neither city's Reckoning faction has achieved archive access.
Midgaard's Reckoning faction coordinates with Kowloon's Reckoning faction on archive access strategy, recognizing simultaneous exposure reduces any single city's relative liability.
The Violet Compact's registry apparatus — processing condemned subjects as "arcane material" — was the mechanism connecting Midgaard's warrant system to the Black Ledger's population transfers.
Charter Sovereignty office files from the Ash-and-Iron period contain references to "delta settlement compliance" and "northern yield processing" — administrative euphemisms for the condemned-debtor transfer system.

flags KOWLOON
---
The Black Ledger's location is known to senior Jade Magistracy clerks and Harbor Syndics' archivists; its contents are not known to either without opening the seal.
The jade seal protocol requiring two magistrates to lift applies to the Black Ledger's physical seal — a deliberate design ensuring no single magistrate could access it unilaterally.
Founding houses debated destroying versus sealing the Ledger: destroying it would eliminate liability; sealing acknowledged liability while deferring consequences.
Argument for sealing: if the Conclave's activities were ever prosecuted inter-city, Kowloon needed to produce evidence of delta settlements' participation rather than face destruction charges.
The argument proved hollow — no inter-city prosecution occurred, and the Black Ledger has remained sealed through two centuries of civic development.
Reckoning faction's current position: the sealing argument is expired; the Conclave is gone, prosecution of specific actors is impossible, and the seal now only protects institutional reputations.
The Neon Covenant's color system was partly designed so no future population category would exist without color-coded institutional visibility, making invisible transfers structurally impossible.

flags KIESS
