Kiess's founding anti-sealed-warrant doctrine was written with specific knowledge of the Black Ledger period — Evermeet's delta trade routes had participated in the same transfer system.
The obsidian disc bearing the Spirebound Conclave's triune seal held by the Syndic Council is Kiess-side documentation of the same institutional chain the Black Ledger records from the delta end.
Kiess's formal position: all sealed Ash-and-Iron period records — Midgaard's trade ledger, Kowloon's Black Ledger, the Violet Compact's arcane-material registry — should open simultaneously under joint five-city commission review.
Simultaneous-opening is designed to prevent any single city bearing disproportionate reputational cost; Kiess's legal team has calculated mutual exposure reduces each city's individual liability proportionally.
Kowloon and Midgaard Continuity factions have declined; their Reckoning factions accepted in principle but lack authority to act.
Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant doctrine creates asymmetry: Kiess has formally repudiated sealed-warrant governance and has less to lose from opening records than cities that have not made that repudiation.

