---
Rakuen's Garden Ledger contains founding-generation entries cross-referencing Midgaard intake registry numbers — records of people who arrived as emergency registrants and were re-registered in Rakuen.
Some dual-registry entries correspond to people whose names appear in Ash Scriptorium cyclic chains cross-referencing Black Ledger period events.
Rakuen's own public records therefore contain indirect evidence of Black Ledger period transfers, through the population that passed through the system and arrived south rather than to the Conclave.
The Bloom Council has considered petitioning for Black Ledger access to match its contents against Garden Ledger founding entries — identifying which founding-population members were processed through the condemned-debtor system.
Political sensitivity is extreme: confirming founding members were processed through the Black Ledger reframes Rakuen's founding population as partly condemned-debtor refugees rather than voluntary settlers.
The distinction matters for annexation petition history: voluntary settlers under welfare mechanisms have different legal standing than condemned-debtor refugees in Midgaard's charter framework.

