---
Umbral archivists in the Gloamvault maintain the most complete external documentation of the Black Ledger period available outside Kowloon's sealed archive.
Documentation accumulated through the Gloamvault's standard practice of recording what passes through underground spaces — condemned-subject transfer routes passed through or near Gloamvault-adjacent passages during the Ash-and-Iron years.
Umbral notation is characteristically precise: absence is documented. Records show which passages were used on which dates, how many people passed through, and when passages were subsequently sealed.
The subsequent sealing of transfer routes is documented in the same neutral administrative terms as any other passage modification — confirming transfers occurred and routes were then hidden.
Umbral archivists have declined to share their documentation with any city's official registry, citing a reciprocal disclosure condition: they will share when a city deposits an equivalent volume of institutional testimony.
The condition has not been met. The Gloamvault record constitutes the most comprehensive unsuppressed account of the Black Ledger period, held outside any city's jurisdiction.
